Has untreated central nervous system metastases;
has a glioma or other primary central nervous system malignant neoplasm;
has spinal cord compression or symptomatic/uncontrolled epidural disease;
history of intracranial hemorrhage or spinal cord hemorrhage;
active neurologic paraneoplastic syndrome;
uncontrolled pleural effusion, pericardial effusion, or ascites requiring recurrent drainage procedures;
active or historical autoimmune disease or immune deficiency (including myasthenia gravis, myositis, autoimmune hepatitis, systemic lupus erythematosus, rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatric arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease, antiphospholipid antibody syndrome, Granulomatosis with polyangiitis, Sjögren’s syndrome, Guillain‑Barré syndrome, multiple sclerosis);
ongoing systemic immunosuppressive medication (>10 mg/day prednisolone-equivalent or equivalents such as cyclophosphamide, azathioprine, methotrexate, thalidomide, TNF‑α inhibitors) within two weeks before starting study treatment;
clinically significant cardiovascular disease (myocardial infarction, symptomatic congestive heart failure New York Heart Association Class III–IV, uncontrolled arrhythmia) within six months;
arterial thrombosis (stroke or transient ischemic attack) within six months;
active viral hepatitis A, B, or C (unless hepatitis B or C is well‑treated with undetectable viral load);
uncontrolled HIV infection (well‑controlled HIV acceptable);
history of allogenic hematopoietic stem cell transplantation or solid‑organ transplantation;
treatment with systemic immunostimulatory agents (interferons, interleukin‑2) within four weeks or five drug elimination half‑lives preceding study entry;
severe hypersensitivity or anaphylaxis to chimeric or humanised antibodies or fusion proteins;
history of interstitial lung disease, idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, organising pneumonia, drug‑induced pneumonitis, or active pneumonitis on baseline CT scan (radiation‑related pneumonitis permissible);
participation in another investigational drug study within three weeks (or five half‑lives) of planned dosing.

