history of interstitial lung disease that is symptomatic or interferes with detection of drug‑related pulmonary toxicity;
active untreated or progressive central nervous system metastases or leptomeningeal disease (except stable, treated brain metastases meeting specified criteria);
significant acute or chronic infections, including known HIV infection or hepatitis B/C infection;
uncontrolled asthma (≥3 indicators of partial control within 28 days before treatment);
current symptomatic congestive heart failure New York Heart Association class III–IV, unstable cardiac arrhythmias, unstable angina, uncontrolled hypertension (>160/>100 mmHg), recent (<6 months) myocardial infarction, coronary or peripheral arterial bypass, stroke or transient ischemic attack;
requirement for long‑term warfarin anticoagulation (vitamin K antagonist);
persistent Grade ≥2 toxicities from prior therapy (excluding alopecia and sensory neuropathy ≤Grade 2);
known severe (Grade ≥3) hypersensitivity to monoclonal antibodies or past anaphylaxis;
vaccination with live agents within 28 days of first study drug dose (only inactivated vaccines permissible);
pregnancy or lactation;
current alcohol or illicit drug dependence;
incarceration or confinement as a prisoner;
psychiatric, social, or other medical conditions deemed by the investigators to substantially increase risk or impair ability to give informed consent or comply with study procedures.

Patients with life‑ threatening immune‑related adverse events associated with prior anti‑PD‑(L)1 therapy, especially Grade 4 events (except controlled thyroid/endocrine disorders) or any event leading to permanent cessation of checkpoint inhibition;
History of ataxia telangiectasia;
Concurrent enrolment in another investigational study;
Allergic reaction to substances chemically or biologically similar to tivusertib or avelumab;
Uncontrolled intercurrent serious illness making participation unsafe;
Inability to ingest oral medication or conditions interfering with drug absorption;
Requirement to continue proton‑pump inhibitor therapy unable to be stopped;
Residual toxicities greater than Grade 1 from prior anticancer therapies (exceptions: alopecia and peripheral neuropathy permissible up to Grade 2; endocrine deficiencies allowable with hormonal replacement);
Use of contraindicated concomitant medicines (strong CYP3A4/CYP1A2 inhibitors or inducers, MATE1/MATE2K substrate drugs such as metformin, acyclovir, estrone sulfate, ciprofloxacin, cephalexin) when unable to substitute;
Chronic systemic glucocorticoid usage exceeding 10 mg/day prednisone equivalents;
Baseline corrected QT interval (QTcF) longer than 470 milliseconds;
Pregnancy or lactation (women of childbearing potential must use approved contraceptive methods; men must use contraception for stipulated periods).

History of another primary malignancy requiring intervention or not in remission for at least three years (unless permitted per protocol);
Unresolved toxicities from prior anticancer therapy exceeding Grade 2;
Active central nervous system involvement by disease under study (excluding stipulated protocol exceptions);
Clinically significant cardiovascular disease;
Primary immunodeficiency disorders;
Stroke or seizure occurring within six months preceding screening;
Autoimmune diseases necessitating systemic immunosuppression or disease-modifying therapy within twenty‑eight days before screening;
Infection with HIV, active hepatitis B, or active hepatitis C viruses;
Ongoing uncontrolled systemic fungal, bacterial, viral, or other infections.

